{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621323"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:52:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:52:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16692"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.77,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9383"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52363"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"5462"},{"type":"tags","id":"5466"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22373"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEvidence-based medicine relies on evaluating the quality and strength of different types of research evidence to inform clinical decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the highest level of evidence in the traditional evidence hierarchy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Randomised controlled trials with adequate sample size","Multi-centre randomised controlled trials","Systematic reviews and meta-analyses of randomised controlled trials","Prospective cohort studies with long-term follow-up","Large population-based epidemiological studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe traditional hierarchy of evidence places \u003Cstrong\u003Esystematic reviews and meta-analyses of randomised controlled trials\u003C/strong\u003E at the highest level. These studies provide the most reliable evidence as they systematically collect, evaluate and synthesise findings from multiple high-quality trials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other study designs represent lower levels of evidence:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandomised controlled trials with adequate sample size\u003C/strong\u003E provide high-quality evidence but examine only a single study population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMulti-centre randomised controlled trials\u003C/strong\u003E improve generalisability; however, they still represent an individual trial. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProspective cohort studies with long-term follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E are observational and cannot control for all confounding factors. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge population-based epidemiological studies\u003C/strong\u003E are susceptible to various forms of bias despite their size. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this hierarchy helps clinicians evaluate and apply evidence appropriately in clinical practice, while recognising that higher-level evidence may not always be available or applicable to every clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The hierarchy of evidence ranks study designs from highest to lowest quality, with systematic reviews and meta-analyses at the top.","Randomised controlled trials provide stronger evidence than observational studies due to their ability to control for confounding factors.","Case reports and expert opinions provide the lowest level of evidence due to their susceptibility to bias and lack of systematic investigation."],"references":["Burns PB, Rohrich RJ, Chung KC. The levels of evidence and their role in evidence-based medicine. Plast Reconstr Surg. 2011 Jul;128(1):305-310. doi: 10.1097/PRS.0b013e318219c171. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3124652/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52363"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52363"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T07:53:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T07:54:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9383"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving informatio